- "Top three counties" refers to the counties with the highest average median income; 
- "Average income level" corresponds to the average median income calculated for each county;
- "Typical vaccination rate" refers to the average vaccination rate for the population aged 12 and up within each county.

- Higher vaccination rates are considered those with an average percentage greater than 50%;
- Notably high social vulnerability refers to a score above 0.6, on a scale typically ranging from 0 to 1;
- Significantly above average is used to denote an above-threshold average vaccination percentage, here defined as greater than 50%.

- 'overall number of vaccine stock entries' refers to the total count of records in the inventory;
- 'typical amount of vaccine per entry' implies the average quantity of vaccine across all entries;
- 'largest amount of vaccine found in a single entry' indicates the highest recorded quantity of vaccine in one entry.
